Youth work in Europe is diverse in its definitions as well as forms and practices. In the context of growing diversity of practices on one hand, and calls for quality standards and professionalisation on the other, the universities have to make their decisions for offering relevant training.

In this context, the focus of the current project is to look at the development of youth work degree programmes as the key factor in successful training of professional youth workers. Under programme development, the project understands the overall design of the study process, the choice of the grounding values and theories, pedagogies, course structure, role of theoretical and practical component, etc. 

Overall, the project aims at improving the quality of youth workers' training in Europe.
The specific objectives of the project are:
1) to work out a model for comparative approach on youth work programmes;
2) to initiate European level dialogue on the challenges of youth work programme development.

The project partnership proposing this project are all involved in youth workers training: University of Tartu from Estonia, Newman University from the UK, Humak University of Applied Sciences from Finland, and Estonian Association of Youth Workers. The project team is formed of 12 experts from the partner universities.

To achieve the project objectives, the team carries out the following activities:
- delivering 1 intellectual output: a book about curriculum development and based on the comparison of the programmes of project  partner universities (named intellectual output book in this application, no better title yet)
- 1 international conference at the end of the project to introduce and disseminate the intellectual output and initiate a discussion on youth workers training in Europe among European youth work community;
- 4 international project meetings;
- 1 staff training event for the project team in preparation for writing the intellectual output;
- 2 round table discussions with policymakers and key stakeholders to benefit from the context of Estonian and Finnish presidency of the Council of EU to draw attention to the project and broader area of youth workers training;
- 1 information dissemination seminar in the UK to introduce the intellectual output;
- 2 sessions of smaller events for local stakeholders.

The desired impact of the project is most anticipated on the European and possibly international level. The project has an ambition to draw European level attention to the importance of organisation and content of the youth workers training. From the policymakers perspective, the project results help to understand the field of youth workers' training and implement accurate supporting policies, both, European and national level. In addition to policymakers, the intellectual output book will be a tool for European universities for their programme development as well as to also grow understanding of other perspectives of designing youth work studies. 

Three of the project partners are universities that provide most sustainable environment for the project results to be maintained and used to produce continuous impact.

“Bump it up!”, Visibility Matters. 
                                                          Dissemination of Erasmus+ projects and open space for European networking
                                                                                                  1th- 8th of March 2015, Dublin

We believe that the key elements of sustainable and successful international youth and community projects are strongly determined by effective and efficient promotion and dissemination of the impact of these projects.  Youth organization may run beautiful projects with young people and youth workers, having great impact on their personal and professional development. But if they don’t spread the word, the results and the benefits for society, the chances are high that due to lack of information and understanding, funders, society, stakeholders and even in their own organizations, the projects lack support. Its a reality that most of the youth organizations face in Europe. At the same time it’s up to those organizations to create a solid and broad foundation among funders, stakeholders and in their own organization. We strongly believe that visibility of youth projects and the dissemination of the project results matters, and this is why we are going to “Bump It Up!”

“Bump It Up!” means formulating a communication strategy, means making your work visible and share your results. In other words, share what you are proud of!  Because this is what we are, we think that youth organizations make a huge contribution to society and now we will make you think the same! 

Joining forces with youth organizations in Europe is thus also an important objective of this training course. In practice this would mean that we spend a substantial part of the programme to  developing strong  partnerships and carry out quality projects. We will  offer  time and  space  for the participants to explore future collaborations  for short term mobility projects and we will strongly support ideas for longer term strategic partnerships. The topic of this training course is par excellence a matter about which we need to formulate long term strategies for our own organization and in collaboration with other youth organizations. 

Let’s start to “Bump It Up!” together with 33 participants from Turkey, Bulgaria, Romania, Greece, Italy, Hungary, United Kingdom, Ireland, Spain, The Netherlands, Georgia, Ukraine, Belgium and Lithuania. Training course is designed for youth and community workers, volunteers, trainers, project managers, community media representatives and any other people who are directly involved working with Erasmus+ projects and/or other type of international collaborations.  Developed a communication strategy that will improve quality, impact and foundation of their (European) youth organization and community projects;
Developed new cooperations with youth organizations throughout Europe. We trust that this training course will contribute to improving quality of Erasmus+ projects and development of competent youth and community workers internationally.

The objective is to explore the concepts and benefits of working on the visibility & dissemination  of (European) youth and community projects by means of a well elaborated communication strategy and to build network between participating organizations. The participants and their organizations as a result:
• Know how to define visibility and dissemination;  
• Know how to analyze why visibility and dissemination is important in international youth and community work; 
• Got acquainted with good practice examples of visibility and dissemination in European youth and community projects;
• Explored different tools and methodology for addressing issues of visibility and dissemination;
• Developed a communication strategy that will improve quality, impact and foundation of their (European) youth organization and community projects;
• Developed new cooperations with youth organizations throughout Europe. 

Training programme consists of 6 different types of activities:
1. Programme activities:  introduction of the day, evaluations, reflections and main lectures on the topic;
2. Team building, energizers and networking activities;
3. Visits and guests workshops/lectures;
4. Communication plan workshop : to set up communication strategies in an ERASMUS+ project and/or youth organization
5. Practical workshops on communication tools and creativity;
6. Communication Living LAB: to arrange visibility and dissemination of the TC in real time both in the street or using “traditional media” or Internet.
